Here's an example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has a ban command:
```js
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');

const client = new Client({
  intents: [Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS],
  shardCount: 'auto',
});

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    // Get the user to be banned
    const userToBan = interaction.options.getUser('user');

    // Check if the user exists and if the user has permission to ban
    if (userToBan && interaction.member.permissionsIn(interaction.guildId).has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      // Get the reason for the ban (optional)
      const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

      // Ban the user
      await interaction.guild.members.ban(userToBan, { reason });

      // Respond to the user with a success message
      await interaction.reply({
        content: `Successfully banned ${userToBan.username}#${userToBan.discriminator}!`,
        ephemeral: true,
      });
    } else {
      // If the user does not exist or if the user does not have permission to ban, respond with an error message
      await interaction.reply({
        content: 'User does not exist or you do not have permission to ban users!',
        ephemeral: true,
      });
    }
  }
});

client.login('your-token-here');
```

This bot listens for the ban command. When invoked, it requires the user to be specified. If a user is specified and the bot has the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission, it will ban the user from the guild and reply with a confirmation message. If no user is specified or the bot does not have the necessary permission, it will send an error message. 

Note that this code assumes you have the `DISCORD_TOKEN` environment variable set to your Discord bot token.

Please be aware that banning users is a powerful action and should be used wisely. Make sure that you have the necessary permissions to ban users in the guild you are operating in. 

Additionally, storing reasons for banning users is a good practice. It can help provide transparency and context for the moderation actions taken in your Discord server. 

You can extend this code to include more commands or add functionality as needed. 

This code uses the v14 version of Discord.js. If you wish to use a different version, the syntax may vary slightly.

Here's an implementation of a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Use a regex to match Markdown syntax and replace with HTML equivalents
    std::regex markdownSyntax(R"([\#\*\-+])\s*(\w*)");

    std::smatch match;
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, markdownSyntax)) {
        std::string markup = match[1];
        std::string text = match[2];

        if (markup == "#") {
            html += "<h1>";
            html += text;
            html += "</h1>\n";
        } else if (markup == "*") {
            html += "<strong>";
            html += text;
            html += "</strong>";
        } else if (markup == "-") {
            html += "<em>";
            html += text;
            html += "</em>";
        } else if (markup == "+") {
            html += "<ul>";
            while (text[text.length() - 1] != '\n') {
                std::string item = text;
                text = "";
                html += "<li>";
                html += item;
                html += "</li>";
            }
            html += "</ul>";
        }

        // Erase the matched Markdown syntax from the string
        markdown.erase(match.position(), match.length());
    }

    // Check for remaining text (not part of any Markdown syntax)
    // and add as paragraphs
    if (!markdown.empty()) {
        html += "<p>";
        html += markdown;
        html += "</p>\n";
    }

    return html;
}
```

This function uses the C++11 `regex` library to convert Markdown syntax to HTML. It matches each Markdown element (e.g., `#` for heading, `*` for bold text, etc.) and replaces it with the appropriate HTML tags. Remaining text, if any, is added as paragraphs.

Remember to compile with a C++11 compatible compiler (e.g., `g++ -std=c++11 filename.cpp`). 

You can test this function by calling it with a Markdown string and printing the resulting HTML. For example:
```cpp
