function checkPrimes(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    let isPrime = true;
    for (let j = 2; j <= Math.sqrt(arr[i]); j++) {
      if (arr[i] % j === 0) {
        isPrime = false;
        break;
      }
    }
    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(arr[i] + " is a prime number.");
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [12, 5, 7, 23, 56];
checkPrimes(numbers);
```

In this code, the `checkPrimes` function takes an array `arr` as input. It then iterates through each number in the array using a for loop. For each number, it checks if it is a prime number by iterating from 2 to the square root of the number and checking if the number is divisible by any integer in that range. If the number is not divisible by any integer, it is a prime number, and the function prints it to the console.

